Airport.Name: Fort Collins Loveland
Report.Status: the student pilot's premature flare resulting in the loss of aircraft control.

Airport.Name: Malcolm McKinnon Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate compensation for wind conditions.  A factor in the accident was the wind gust.

Airport.Name: Kodiak
Report.Status: The failure of company maintenance personnel to ensure that the airplane's nose baggage door latching mechanism was properly configured and maintained, resulting in an inadvertent opening of the nose baggage door in flight. Contributing to the accident were the lack of information and guidance available to the operator and pilot regarding procedures to follow should a baggage door open in flight and an inadvertent aerodynamic stall.
A loss of engine power due to inadequate maintenance inspection resulting in a worn throttle housing going undetected and failing.

Airport.Name: LINCOLN MUNI
Report.Status: The improper installation of the swivel valve fittings by the operator's mechanic leading to the total loss of both hydraulic systems.  Contributing to the incident were the swivel valves leaking and the total failure of the hydraulic system.

Airport.Name: Detroit Metro
Report.Status: The separation of the engine cowling which resulted from maintenance personnel failing to follow maintenance procedures in that they did not latch the engine cowling following the maintenance inspection.  A factor associated with the accident was their attention was divereted from the task when another mechanic asked for assistance.
The pilot's improper decision to takeoff from an inadequate field after a forced landing.

Airport.Name: Lihue
Report.Status: The pilot's spatial disorientation and loss of situational awareness. Contributing to the accident were the dark night and the task requirements of simultaneously monitoring the cockpit instruments and the other airplane.

Airport.Name: San Francisco International
Report.Status: The company tug operator of the other airplane's failure to maintain clearance with this aircraft during the pushback process.  Also causal was the ground controller's failure to alert the pilot of this aircraft and tug operator of the other airplane of the simultaneous pushback occurring from adjacent gates.  Contributing to the accident was the company's pushback operation without the use of wing/tail walkers.

Airport.Name: Bethel
Report.Status: The pilot's selection of unsuitable terrain for landing. Contributing to the accident were snow-covered terrain, blowing snow and flat lighting conditions.

Airport.Name: Aniak
Report.Status: A partial loss of engine power for an undetermined reason. Contributing to the accident were the pilot's inadvertent encounter with IMC conditions, and a whiteout during his attempted go-around from an emergency landing approach.

Airport.Name: ford Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's loss of control on landing.  A factor was a gusting crosswind component.

Airport.Name: BURKE LAKEFRONT
Report.Status: The pilot experienced spatial disorientation during the inital climb causing him to lose control of the airplane.

Airport.Name: Tulsa International Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's loss of control due to spatial disorientation and the pilot exceeding the design/stress limits of the aircraft.  Factors contributing to the accident were the pilot's reported gyro problem,  the dark night conditions ,  and prevailing instrument meteorological conditions.

Airport.Name: Dutch Harbor
Report.Status: The disengagement of the rudder control cable and loose rudder cable retaining pins. A factor contributing to the accident was a wind gust.
An in-flight loss of control and an uncontrolled descent into terrain for undetermined reasons.
The student pilot's failure to maintain directional control of the airplane during the landing roll.  Contributing to the accident were the snow-covered runway and the gusty wind conditions.

Airport.Name: St. Louis/Downtown
Report.Status: Maintenance personnel's improper replacement of the landing gear leg brace assembly which subsequently failed to keep the landing gear in the locked position.

Airport.Name: Newark Liberty Intl
Report.Status: a fault in the airplane's AC 1 electrical bus that caused a number of other electrical busses on the aircraft to lose power.

Airport.Name: Carroll County Regional
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper flare.

Airport.Name: Canon Ranch Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain sufficient airspeed while maneuvering which resulted in a stall.

Airport.Name: Dawson Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during landing roll out.

Airport.Name: North Perry
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control while landing. Contributing was the gusty crosswind condition.

Airport.Name: Charlotte/Douglas Internationa
Report.Status: The tug driver's failure to stop for a taxiway stop sign.
the arcing of the windshield heat system at the upper, aft (J1) and upper, forward (J4) terminal locations on the first officer's windshield, which caused the inner pane of glass to fracture.

Airport.Name: Palo Alto Airport
Report.Status: Loss of engine power during the takeoff initial climb due to lack of compression to a cylinder.

Airport.Name: Fort Lauderdal Executive
Report.Status: The depletion of pressure in the normal hydraulic system for an undetermined reason, and the pilots' failure to properly operate the emergency braking system. Contributing to the accident was an inoperative hydraulic system aural warning.

Airport.Name: Lindsay Municipal
Report.Status: The flight instructor's failure to maintain control of the airplane, which resulted in an inadvertent stall while maneuvering.
The encounter with severe turbulence causing serious injury to the flight attendant.

Airport.Name: Ankeny Regional Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during the takeoff roll.  Contributing to the accident was the snow on the runway and the snowbank.

Airport.Name: Tatitna Airstrip
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control of the airplane during an aborted takeoff.

Airport.Name: Austin Bergstrom International
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain control of the airplane while parked on the ramp with the engine running.

Airport.Name: Dekalb-Peachtree Airport
Report.Status: A cracked nose gear actuator o-ring resulting in hydraulic fluid exhaustion, and collapse of the main gear.

Airport.Name: Chefornak
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain control of the airplane during the landing flare/touchdown.

Airport.Name: San Antonio International
Report.Status: Separation of the turbocharger exhaust stack, which resulted in a loss of engine power.
an in-flight collision with a bird.

Airport.Name: St. Louis Downtown Airport
Report.Status: The flight instructor's failure to correct for proper runway alignment during final approach and his failure to maintain aircraft control during his subsequent go-around.  Contributing to the accident was the dual-student's failure to properly align with the runway centerline during final approach and the dark night.

Airport.Name: Arlington Municipal
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper landing flare resulting in a hard landing.  Contributing to the accident were the gusty surface winds and the student pilot's inadequate preflight planning.
The loss of engine power for undetermined reasons.  Contributing factors were the lack of suitable terrain for the forced landing and dark night conditions.

Airport.Name: Logan-Cache Airport
Report.Status: The dual-student's excessive brake application, and the flight instructor's inadequate supervision of the flight.

Airport.Name: Sky Ranch Airport at Carefree
Report.Status: The collapse of the landing gear during landing rollout for undetermined reasons.

Airport.Name: REYKJAVIK AD ARPT (NOF)
Report.Status: The reported loss of both engines' power during cruise for undetermined reasons.

Airport.Name: Centennial Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's improper decision to fly the airplane with a discharged battery, which resulted in a total electrical failure during takeoff climb.  Contributing factors were the pilot's inability to verify the landing gear position, and the impact with the runway sign.
The loss of pitch control during cruise flight resulting from the separation of the stabilator trim actuator due to inadequate maintenenace.

Airport.Name: Hilo International Airport
Report.Status: The captain and first officer inadvertently falling asleep during the cruise phase of flight. Contributing to the incident were the captain's undiagnosed obstructive sleep apnea and the flight crews recent work schedules, which included several consecutive days of early-morning start times.
The pilot not maintaining clearance from the runway sign during taxi for takeoff.  A factor contributing to the accident was an icy taxiway.

Airport.Name: Leesburg Executive Airport
Report.Status: The airplane's runway excursion during landing roll following an encounter with ice.  Contributing to the accident was the ice-covered runway, and the airport personnel's lack of knowledge regarding the runway condition.

Airport.Name: Gainesville Regional Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's improper flare.

Airport.Name: Dillingham Airfield
Report.Status: The failure of the left main landing gear strut due to fatigue. Contributing to the failure was the side load placed on the landing gear while making a crosswind landing.
The flight attendant's inadvertent slip on the galley's contaminated floor and falling during climb to cruise.

Airport.Name: Orlando International Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's inadequate recovery from a bounced landing.

Airport.Name: Gillespie Field
Report.Status: The failure of both pilots to maintain directional control during landing and the flight instructor's inadequate supervision of the flight.

Airport.Name: Washington Reagan
Report.Status: Inadequate ground separation maintained by the pilot of the Embraer E170.

Airport.Name: Austin Bergstrom International
Report.Status: The airplane struck a large bird while making a visual approach to the airport.

Airport.Name: QUAD-CITY
Report.Status: The arcing of the resistor and silicone controlled rectifier in the flap control circuit.

Airport.Name: Arnold Field
Report.Status: The flight instructor's inadequate remedial action. Contributing to the accident was the student pilot's failure to maintain directional control during the landing roll.

Airport.Name: Perry-Houston County Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's inadequate compensation for wind conditions during landing. Contributing to the accident were the gusting winds.
The pilot's decision to fly into an area of forecast weather suitable for structural icing.  Contributing to the accident was the effect of the structural icing encountered.

Airport.Name: Aniak
Report.Status: The captain's inadequate compensation for wind conditions during the landing flare/touchdown. Contributing to the accident were a crosswind and windshear.

Airport.Name: Peabody Bedard Field
Report.Status: The flight crew's failure to execute a missed approach, which resulted in a runway excursion after landing. Contributing to the accident were the inoperative lights, weather conditions below published approach minimums, and the slush contaminated runway.

Airport.Name: Greater Cumberland Regional
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain the proper approach course for undetermined reasons.

Airport.Name: Orlando International
Report.Status: An unexpected encounter with turbulence, while on approach for landing.

Airport.Name: McCarran International Airport
Report.Status: An inadvertent encounter with severe turbulence during descent and the failure of two passenger seat belt attach fittings.  Contributing to the incident was the failure of the operator to comply with the SAIB.

Airport.Name: Jackson Hole
Report.Status: the loss of braking action on the left main landing gear due to the cross connection of the wheel speed tachometer wires that was caused by inadequate maintenance performed on the airplane during the installation of the main landing gear.

Airport.Name: Tampa International Airport
Report.Status: The malfunction of the right main landing gear down-and-locked switch.

Airport.Name: GILA BEND MUNI
Report.Status: The flight crew's inadvertent retraction of the landing gear during the landing roll, and the flight instructor's inadequate supervision of the flight.

Airport.Name: Vero Beach Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's failure to maintain directional control of the airplane during an aborted takeoff.

Airport.Name: DALLAS LOVE FIELD
Report.Status: The failure of the taxiing flight crew to maintain an adequate clearance from the stationary airplane.

Airport.Name: Lincoln Park
Report.Status: The certificated flight instructor's delayed decision to go-around.

Airport.Name: Norwood Memorial Airport
Report.Status: The failure of the flightcrew to maintain directional control of the airplane.

Airport.Name: CENTRE MUNI
Report.Status: The pilot's improper landing flare, resulting in a hard landing.

Airport.Name: Chandler Municipal
Report.Status: The student pilot's delay in initiating the go-around, and the flight instructor's inadequate supervision of the flight and delayed remedial action. Contributing to the accident were the momentary failure of the engine to respond, the failure of both the student and the instructor to adhere to the operator's procedures, and the rough/uneven terrain.
Airplane wing-structure damage sustained during impact with one or more large birds (American white pelicans), which resulted in a loss of control of the airplane.
The flight instructor's inadequate evaluation of  the weather conditions. Contributing to the accident was an inadvertent stall/mush.

Airport.Name: JEROME COUNTY
Report.Status: The failure of both pilots to maintain directional control of the airplane during takeoff.

Airport.Name: Witham Field
Report.Status: The flight crew's failure to reset the brakes circuit breaker resulting in a loss of brakes during taxi and an on ground collision with an unoccupied parked airplane.

Airport.Name: New Jerusalem Airport
Report.Status: The flight instructor's inadequate compensation for the tailwind condition and failure to maintain adequate airspeed that led to an inadvertent stall.

Airport.Name: Richmond International Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper flare, which resulted in a hard landing.
The loss of engine power for undetermined reasons.  Contributing to the accident were the sign and a vehicle.

Airport.Name: DESERT ROCK
Report.Status: A loss of power to both engines resulting from a fitting failure and leak at the right fuel selector valve that allowed fuel from the right tank to be lost overboard, and that then introduced air into the left engine's fuel lines during an attempted cross-feed operation.

Airport.Name: Spartanburg Downtown Memorial
Report.Status: The pilot's encounter with wake turbulence during approach as a result of his inadequate in-flight planning.

Airport.Name: Richfield Municipal
Report.Status: The pilot's improper use of the flight controls and failure to maintain directional control.

Airport.Name: Okeechobee County Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain an adequate airspeed while maneuvering at low altitude. Contributing to the accident was the overweight condition of the airplane and the inoperative stall warning horn.
The pilot's failure to maintain directional control of the aircraft.  A contributing factor was the wet, grass runway.
The failure of the pilot to maintain airspeed while maneuvering.

Airport.Name: FORT LAUDERDALE EXECUTIVE
Report.Status: The improper adjustment of the right main landing gear down lock by maintenance personnel resulting in the gear collapse during the landing roll..

Airport.Name: Phoenix Deer Valley
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate compensation for the crosswind condition and failure to maintain directional control during the landing roll.  Contributing to the accident was the crosswind condition.
The pilot's inadequate compensation for wind conditions.  Factors contributing to the accident are high and gusting winds.
The pilot's misjudgment of the landing flare and her inadequate recovery from the bounced landing.

Airport.Name: Opa Locka Airport
Report.Status: The entanglement of the hook rope with the rudder horn during banner pickup.

Airport.Name: Falcon Field
Report.Status: A partial loss of engine power for undetermined reasons.

Airport.Name: Portland
Report.Status: The failure of company maintenance personnel to install the upper pivot bolt through the pivot hole in the upper end of the landing gear actuating rod, and the company maintenance inspector's inadequate inspection of the work performed.

Airport.Name: New Albany
Report.Status: A loss of engine power for undetermined reasons.

Airport.Name: Richard B. Russell
Report.Status: The flight instructor's failure to maintain aircraft control while maneuvering during a simulated engine failure. Contributing to the accident was the flight instructor's lack of total experience as a multiengine flight instructor.

Airport.Name: PUEBLO MEMORIAL
Report.Status: the failure of the student pilot, and then the flight instructor to maintain aircraft control during the landing.  Contributing factors were the flight instructor's delayed remedial action, and the crosswind conditions.

Airport.Name: Inverness Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper landing flare and the flight examiner's inadequate remedial action.

Airport.Name: Heimgartner Airstrip
Report.Status: The in-flight failure of the rudder attachment point due to severe corrosion, which made directional control of the airplane not possible during landing.

Airport.Name: Whitman County Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate compensation for the wind conditions, failure to attain and maintain an adequate airspeed that resulted in a stall mush, and, the subsequent failure to maintain terrain and obstacle clearance during the takeoff initial climb. Contributing factors were the tailwind weather condition, and the one-way direction requirements of the airstrip.

The installed wing panel clips failed due to fatigue, likely caused by the incorrect installation of the fasteners in response to SB 757-57-0027.  Contributing to the incorrect installation was the SB's lack of clarity in the instructions and figures on the correct orientation of the clips and spacers.

Airport.Name: Private
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate compensation for the wind conditions and failure to maintain an adequate airspeed.  A contributing factor was the sudden windshift.
The pilot's failure to maintain terrain clearance.  Contributing factors were the dusk light condition and the pressure the pilot felt to accomplish the flight.

The pilot failed to maintain situational awareness during the flight. Contributing to the accident were the dark night, the pilot's failure to follow approved navigational procedures for the flight, and the pilot's over reliance on the avionics in the airplane.

Airport.Name: Page Municipal
Report.Status: The flight crews unprofessional behavior and deviation from standard operating procedures which resulted in an in-flight emergency.

Airport.Name: CHERRY CAPITAL
Report.Status: The unstabalized approach performed by the student pilot and the go-around not performed by the student pilot. Additional causes were the inadequate recovery from a bounced landing and the directional control not obtained by the student pilot. Contributing factors were the wind gusts and the student pilots lack of total experience.

Airport.Name: Private
Report.Status: A loss of engine power as a result of a blocked carburetor.  A factor was the lack of suitable terrain for the forced landing.

Airport.Name: Henderson Executive Airport
Report.Status: The failure of the left main landing gear torque link assembly for undetermined reasons.

Airport.Name: George Bush Intercontinental
Report.Status: The flight crew's improper landing technique for an inoperative anti-skid system resulting in locked brakes and four blown main landing gear tires.
A propeller malfunction for undetermined reasons.

Airport.Name: MANKATO
Report.Status: the student pilot's failure to maintain directional control during the takeoff roll.  Contributing factors were the fence and trees.

Airport.Name: Phoenix Deer Valley
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control of the airplane during landing.

Airport.Name: Buckeye Municipal Airport
Report.Status: A loss of engine power for undetermined reasons.  Contributing to the accident was the soft terrain.

Airport.Name: Gillespie Field
Report.Status: the student pilot's inadequate compensation for gusty, crosswind conditions, and failure to maintain an adequate airspeed.

Airport.Name: Benson Municipal
Report.Status: The pilot's misjudged speed and altitude during approach that led to a long landing and his subsequent failure to maintain control during an attempted go-around.  Contributing to the accident were the dark night, the pilot's low total night flight experience, and low total time in the make and model airplane.

Airport.Name: John F. Kennedy Intl Airport
Report.Status: The co-pilot's failure to maintain directional control during the landing roll. Contributing to the accident was a loss of system A hydraulic fluid for undetermined reasons and the flight crew's failure to follow the checklist sequence.

Airport.Name: Tuscaloosa Regional Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's encounter with severe turbulence during descent into the airport environment, which resulted in an exceedence of the aircraft's design stress limit and structural damage.

Airport.Name: ANCHORAGE INTL
Report.Status: The flightcrew's misjudged flare while landing.

Airport.Name: Shelby County Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to utilize carburetor heat during a power off approach.

Airport.Name: NONE
Report.Status: Fatigue failure and separation of the propeller during cruise flight.  Contributing to the accident was the owner's failure to comply with a long standing Airworthiness Directive.
An undetermined mechanical malfuction associated with the tail rotor drive system which led to a loss of control.

Airport.Name: Ryan Field
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate compensation for the gusty wind condition, which resulted in a loss of control and impact with terrain while landing. A contributing factor was the gusty wind condition.

Airport.Name: San Luis County Regional

Airport.Name: Miami International Airport
Report.Status: An unexpected encounter with turbulence, during the initial descent for landing.

Report.Status: The student pilot's loss of directional control on landing. Contributing to the accident was the crosswind and wind gusts.
the impact with a bird during initial takeoff climb.

Airport.Name: Redding Municipal
Report.Status: The failure of the pilot under instruction to lower the landing gear, the failure of both pilots to follow the landing checklist, and the flight instructor's inadequate supervision of the flight.
The improper installation of the fuel manifold valve's brass plug.  Contributing to the accident was the unsuitable landing area for the forced landing.

Airport.Name: McClellan-Palomar
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate crosswind compensation and failure to maintain directional control during landing rollout.

Airport.Name: Unalaska Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain clearance from a truck while landing, and the vehicle operator's decision to ignore runway warning signals. Contributing to the accident was an inoperative vehicle gate system and the failure of airport management to adequately maintain the gate system and issue a NOTAM.

Airport.Name: Roswell International Air Cent
Report.Status: The airframe and powerplant  mechanic's incorrect reassembly of the landing gear.

Airport.Name: Potsdam Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during landing.
The pilot's failure to maintain airplane control on the landing roll.  A contributing factor was the variable wind.

The pilot's failure to maintain an adequate airspeed while maneuvering that led to an inadvertent stall.  A contributing factor in the accident was the low altitude of the flight that reduced the time available for recovery from an upset.

Airport.Name: Youngstown Elser Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain adequate airspeed, resulting in an aerodynamic stall.

Airport.Name: Westchester County
Report.Status: An uncommanded landing gear retraction after touchdown for undetermined reasons.

Report.Status: The flight instructor's decision to attempt takeoff with an engine discrepancy and subsequent failure to abort takeoff when the airplane did not attain adequate airspeed during the initial climb, resulting in an aerodynamic stall. Contributing to the accident was the partial loss of engine power.

Airport.Name: Tyndall AFB
Report.Status: The pilot's misjudged flare and subsequent hard landing, and her inadequate recovery from a bounced landing.
The pilot's inadequate visual lookout and his failure to maintain clearance from the tranmission lines. A factor in this accident was the unmarked transmission wires.

Airport.Name: Brackett Field
Report.Status: A loss of engine power in the left engine due to fuel starvation as a result of the pilot's inadequate preflight inspection and the pilot's failure to abort the takeoff following the power loss.

The pilot's failure to maintain aircraft control following the jettison of the load during an aerial fire flighting mission, which resulted in an inadvertent stall and impact with terrain.  Contributing to the accident were the improperly configured aircraft for the flight, the gusty wind conditions, and the pressure to complete the mission.

Airport.Name: Rowan County Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper flare during landing.

The inadvertent stalling of the rudder trim actuator motor during flight due to the pilot's unintentional exceedence of the motor's design limit for stalling while accelerating after completing a simulated engine-out maneuver.

The pilot's failure to maintain airspeed while maneuvering, resulting in an aerodynamic stall and loss of aircraft control.  Contributing to the accident were rising mountainous terrain and a high density altitude.

Airport.Name: SKANEATELES AERO DROME
Report.Status: The certified flight instructor's failure to maintain airspeed during a steep turn.

The pilot's failure to maintain adequate airspeed, resulting in an inadvertent stall/spin. Contributing factors in this accident were the entanglement of the parachute in the elevator control system, reducing the pilot's ability to regain control.

Airport.Name: LA PORTE MUNI
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper recovery from the bounced landing and the instructor's delayed remedial action.
The pilot's failure to maintain clearance from electrical wires while maneuvering.  Contributing to the accident were binding of the elevator control, inadvertent stall and trees.

Airport.Name: Daytona Beach International
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper recovery from a bounced landing.

Report.Status: An engine fire in the No. 3 engine due to the failure of, and subsequent flammable fluid leak from, one of three fuel or hydraulic lines located in the engine's accessory raceway that ignited when the fluid came in contact with the hot engine cases. Report.Status: A loss of control during the landing roll due to a failure or malfunction of the brake system, resulting in a loss of control, and structural damage to the airplane.

Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain an adequate airspeed during climb out resulting in an aerodynamic stall/spin.

Airport.Name: Seven Rivers Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's improper decision to takeoff uphill with full fuel and fuel chemical load.  A factor was the pilot's failure to calculate performance data.

Airport.Name: Tetlin Airport
Report.Status: The instructor pilot's inadequate supervision of the student, resulting in a loss of control while landing.

Contributing to the accident were the restricted forward visibility of the tail-wheel equipped Spitfire, the lack of communication to the other aircraft following the Hurricane, and the limited view of the runway by the airboss.
The pilot's failure to maintain clearance from the terrain while maneuvering at low altitude. Contributing to the accident was the rising terrain.

Airport.Name: Cleburne Municipal
Report.Status: The failure of the flight instructor and student pilot to extend the landing gear prior to the airplane touching down on the runway.

Airport.Name: Erie Municipal
Report.Status: The pilot failed to maintain directional control of the airplane during the touch and go landing.
The pilot's selection of an unsuitable landing site, which resulted in an overload failure of the tail ski assembly during the landing roll.

Airport.Name: Greenwood Municipal
Report.Status: The student pilot's failure to maintain control of the airplane during engine run-up.

Airport.Name: Port Heiden
Report.Status: The flying pilots failure to maintain directional control while landing in a crosswind.  A factor contributing to the accident was a crosswind.

The pilot's failure to maintain adequate altitude during a course reversal at the completion of an agricultural spray run.
the pilot's failure to maintain clearance with the power line.

Report.Status: The pilot's improper decision to attempt to close the canopy in flight, and his diverted attention resulting in the airplane impacting the terrain.  Contributing to the accident was the excessively worn canopy latch.
A total loss of engine power during takeoff due to fuel exhaustion as a result of the pilot's failure to verify the fuel quantity prior to flight.

Airport.Name: Glendale
Report.Status: The pilot's misjudged landing flare and inadequate recovery from a bounced landing.

Airport.Name: Homestead
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper flare. Contributing to the accident was the flight instructor's inadequate remedial action.

Airport.Name: Phoenix-Mesa Gateway Airport
Report.Status: The loss of aircraft control due to an undetermined rudder malfunction.

Airport.Name: THOMAS P STAFFORD

The lugs cracked due to loss of material and resultant increase in stress load on the blade slot serrations due to excessve grit blasting when the hub was being overhauled  by Delta Air Lines. On August 26, 2008, about 1100 local time, a Cessna 172, Ecuadorian registration HC-BKY, registered to an operated by Wings of Hope Incorporated, as a medical transport flight, crashed following a loss of engine power, while in cruise flight to Rio Amazonas Airport, Pastaza, Ecuador. Visual meteorological conditions prevailed, and no flight plan was filed. The airplane was substantial damage. The private-rated pilot and passenger received serious injuries. 

According to information obtained from the Ecuadorian Subdireccion de Aviacion Civil, the pilot reported total loss of engine power, while in cruise flight. He conducted an emergency landing, and crashed into trees.

This investigation is under the jurisdiction of the Government of Ecuador. Any further information can be obtained from:

The operators inadequate maintenance of the airplanes tires, which resulted in multiple tire failures during takeoff roll due to severe underinflation, and the captains execution of a rejected takeoff (RTO) after V1, which was inconsistent with her training and standard operating procedures. 
Contributing to the accident were (1) deficiencies in Learjets design of and the Federal Aviation Administrations (FAA) certification of the Learjet Model 60s thrust reverser system, which permitted the failure of critical systems in the wheel well area to result in uncommanded forward thrust that increased the severity of the accident; (2) the inadequacy of Learjets safety analysis and the FAAs review of it, which failed to detect and correct the thrust reverser and wheel well design deficiencies after a 2001 uncommanded forward thrust accident; (3) inadequate industry training standards for flight crews in tire failure scenarios; and (4) the flight crews poor crew resource management (CRM).

Airport.Name: New York La Guardia
Report.Status:
The ingestion of large birds into each engine, which resulted in an almost total loss of thrust in both engines and the subsequent ditching on the Hudson River. Contributing to the fuselage damage and resulting unavailability of the aft slide/rafts were (1) the Federal Aviation Administrations approval of ditching certification without determining whether pilots could attain the ditching parameters without engine thrust, (2) the lack of industry flight crew training and guidance on ditching techniques, and (3) the captains resulting difficulty maintaining his intended airspeed on final approach due to the task saturation resulting from the emergency situation.

Contributing to the survivability of the accident was (1) the decision-making of the flight crewmembers and their crew resource management during the accident sequence; (2) the fortuitous use of an airplane that was equipped for an extended overwater flight, including the availability of the forward slide/rafts, even though it was not required to be so equipped; (3) the performance of the cabin crewmembers while expediting the evacuation of the airplane; and (4) the proximity of the emergency responders to the accident site and their immediate and appropriate response to the accident.

Airport.Name: Washington Dulles
Report.Status:
The ignition of the J5 power terminal located on the captains No. 1 windshield due to a loose electrical connection between the terminal connector lug and its respective terminal block. The loose connection resulted from a missing lock washer that allowed the resistance in the electrical path to increase sufficiently to generate high enough temperatures to ignite the terminal block.

Contributing to the probable cause was the lack of instructions to ensure the lock washer was installed in the J5 power terminal block in the Boeing 757 aircraft maintenance manual (AMM). 

Additionally, contributing to the incident was the deferral of the related maintenance write-up before the incident, which resulted from information in the United Airlines AMM that stated, When bus bar(s) show signs of blackening or burning, the condition is acceptable for continued service, although the window must be replaced within 50 flight-hours.

The internal fuel pressure then forced open the fuel manifold cover at the location of the missing bolt, causing a gap between the two mating surfaces which allowed fuel to push past the integral packing, resulting in a fuel leak onto the hot engine cases where it ignited resulting in a fire.

Report.Status:
The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident as follows: 

an aerodynamic stall and subsequent uncommanded roll during a one engine-inoperative takeoff flight test, which were the result of (1) Gulfstreams failure to properly develop and validate takeoff speeds for the flight tests and recognize and correct the takeoff safety speed (V2) error during previous G650 flight tests, (2) the G650 flight test teams persistent and increasingly aggressive attempts to achieve V2 speeds that were erroneously low, and (3) Gulfstreams inadequate investigation of previous G650 uncommanded roll events, which indicated that the companys estimated stall angle of attack while the airplane was in ground effect was too high. Contributing to the accident was Gulfstreams failure to effectively manage the G650 flight test program by pursuing an aggressive program schedule without ensuring that the roles and responsibilities of team members had been appropriately defined and implemented, engineering processes had received sufficient technical planning and oversight, potential hazards had been fully identified, and appropriate risk controls had been implemented and were functioning as intended.

Airport.Name: Reno/Stead Airport
Report.Status: The reduced stiffness of the elevator trim tab system that allowed aerodynamic flutter to occur at racing speeds. The reduced stiffness was a result of deteriorated locknut inserts that allowed the trim tab attachment screws to become loose and to initiate fatigue cracking in one screw sometime before the accident flight. Aerodynamic flutter of the trim tabs resulted in a failure of the left trim tab link assembly, elevator movement, high flight loads, and a loss of control. Contributing to the accident were the undocumented and untested major modifications to the airplane and the pilots operation of the airplane in the unique air racing environment without adequate flight testing.

Airport.Name: Denver International
Report.Status:
**This probable cause was modified on 4/5/2012. Please see the public docket for this accident to view the original probable cause.**


The initial damage to the fan blades was caused by the ingestion of a Red-Tailed Hawk that caused one or more fan blades to fracture, striking the fan case and causing it to bulge. The initial fan blade fragment release impacted and damaged other passing fan blades generating various sized blades fragments. Some of these blade fragments were propelled forward of the fan case by passing fan blades and were reingested, creating a cascading effect of collateral impact damage to the other fan blades, the fan case, and the inlet cowl.

Report.Status: The flight instructor's failure to maintain airspeed above the air minimum control airspeed (Vmca), which resulted in a loss of control and impact with terrain. Contributing to the accident was the instructor's failure to follow published procedures to retract the landing gear and maintain 85 knots minimum airspeed during the one-engine-inoperative go-around maneuver.
The pilots failure to maintain clearance from the ground due to his distraction with programming a global positioning system receiver.

Airport.Name: Frederick Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The student pilots inadequate directional control during the landing roll.

Airport.Name: Key West International
Report.Status: The pilots failure to appropriately apply the landing gear wheel brakes after landing, to properly perform the hard brake pedal-no braking condition procedure following the reported brake failure and to apply the emergency brakes. The reason for the reported brake failure could not be determined because postincident examination did not reveal any malfunctions or failures that would have precluded normal operation of the brakes.

Airport.Name: Fort Lauderdale Executive
Report.Status: The Cessna 172 flight instructor and student pilot's inadequate visual lookout and failure to maintain clearance from the stationary Cessna 182.

Airport.Name: Wings Field Airport
Report.Status: The flight instructor's failure to maintain airspeed in changing wind conditions during a steep climb after takeoff, which resulted in an aerodynamic stall. Contributing to the accident was the flight instructors ostentatious display close to the ground.

Airport.Name: Yucca Valley Airport
Report.Status: A loss of engine power for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examination did not reveal any anomalies that would have precluded normal operation.

Airport.Name: Kwigillingok
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to abort the takeoff when he realized the airplane could not attain sufficient takeoff and climb performance and his improper decision to depart from an airport where night operations were prohibited.

Airport.Name: Private
Report.Status: A total loss of engine power during takeoff initial climb for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examination did not reveal any anomalies that would have precluded normal operation.

Airport.Name: Cheyenne Regional Airport
Report.Status: The flight crews failure to properly latch the cabin door before takeoff.

Airport.Name: Kissimee Gateway
Report.Status: A fatigue failure of the right main landing gear pivot assembly, which prevented the landing gear from extending.
The total loss of engine power from both engines, which resulted from fuel exhaustion due to the pilots inadequate pre-flight preparation.

Airport.Name: MINNEAPOLIS-ST PAUL INTL/WOLD-
Report.Status: In-flight collision with birds during initial climb, which resulted in substantial damage to the aircraft.

Airport.Name: Sturgis Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The student pilots failure to maintain control of the airplane during takeoff with extended flaps.

Airport.Name: Mettel Field Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control of the airplane during landing.
Ice accretion in the main landing gear wheel brakes, which prevented the main landing gear wheels from rotating on landing, which resulted in the airplane nosing over.

Airport.Name: Kissimmee Gateway Airport
Report.Status: The passengers fall from the airplane during a normal egress.

Airport.Name: Bishop International Airport
Report.Status: The captain's failure to maintain directional control during landing with one engine inoperative. Contributing to the accident was an improperly installed clevis pin in the left engine power lever, the crews delay in accurately identifying their heading, and their subsequent selection of a runway with a strong crosswind.

The total loss of left engine power due to fuel starvation, and the pilots improper configuration of the fuel system during remedial actions, which resulted in fuel starvation of the right engine. Contributing to the accident was the pilots incomplete preflight inspection and the pilots operation of the airplane with a known faulty fuel quantity indicating system.

Airport.Name: Pilot Country Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's incorrect identification of the runway, which resulted in an off-airport landing and subsequent collision with objects.

Airport.Name: Quad Cities International
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain clearance from the parked, unoccupied airplane while taxiing. Contributing to the accident was the guidance provided by the marshaller.
A broken wheel/ski clevis pin, which allowed the ski to pivot upward and strike the right wing lift strut.

The total loss of engine power during cruise flight for reasons that could not be determined because the airplane was not recovered. Contributing to the accident was the pilots failure to comply with the airplane and engine limitations, and his decision to fly over water beyond power-off gliding distance from shore.

Airport.Name: Napa County Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper landing flare, inadequate recovery from a bounced landing, and loss of directional control.

Airport.Name: Chicago Executive Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate preflight planning and in-flight decision-making, which resulted in a loss of engine power due to fuel exhaustion during approach. Contributing to the accident was the pilot's decision to operate an airplane after using illicit drugs.
The pilots loss of situational awareness after an inadvertent encounter with instrument meteorological conditions, which resulted in an in-flight collision with tree-covered terrain.

Airport.Name: Lakefront Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's fatal  cardiac event, which resulted in the inflight loss of control of the airplane. Contributing to the accident was the pilot's use of impairing medications and operation of the airplane with disqualifying medical conditions.

Airport.Name: Boeing Field/King County Inter
Report.Status: The flight instructors failure to maintain airplane control during a go-around.
The flight's encounter with known severe turbulence associated with mountain wave activity, which resulted in a flight attendant sustaining a broken ankle.

Airport.Name: Chicago Midway
Report.Status: The tower local controller did not ensure that the runway was clear of conflict before directing the B737 to cross the runway, and other air traffic control personnel did not effectively intervene when the separation between the two airplanes became questionable.

Airport.Name: Midland Airpark
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain the recommended airspeed for icing conditions and his subsequent loss of airplane control while flying the airplane under autopilot control in severe icing conditions, contrary to the airplane's handbook. Contributing to the accident was the pilot's failure to divert from an area of severe icing. Also contributing to the accident was the lack of an advisory for potential hazardous icing conditions over the destination area.
Water contamination in the pitch trim actuators.

Airport.Name: San Carlos Airport
Report.Status: The collapse of the right main landing gear during the turn off the runway due to the failure of the A-frame assembly.

Airport.Name: Oakland International Airport
Report.Status: The flight crews flight into known severe turbulence associated with mountain wave activity.

Airport.Name: Fulton County
Report.Status: The student pilot's loss of directional control during landing.

Airport.Name: Denver International Airport
Report.Status: A failure of the nose landing gear end cap due to fatigue. Contributing to the failure were the ineffective inspection and the unknown effect of grain direction on fatigue life.
The pilots decision to initiate visual flight in instrument meteorological conditions and subsequent failure to maintain adequate altitude.
The failure of a crankshaft gear tooth due to fatigue, which resulted in the loss of several additional gear teeth and a subsequent total loss of engine power.

Airport.Name: Yolo County
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate fuel management, which resulted in a loss of engine power due to fuel starvation.

Airport.Name: Festus Memorial Airport
Report.Status: The certified flight instructors delayed remedial action as the airplane neared an aerodynamic stall/spin. Contributing to the accident was that the student pilot did not maintain adequate airspeed during the go-around attempt.

Airport.Name: Kaltag
Report.Status: The pilot landed without lowering the landing gear. Contributing to the accident was the pilot's self-reported fatigue.

Airport.Name: Clermont County
Report.Status: A loss of engine power due to failure of the engine oil cooler and subsequent oil starvation to the engine.

Airport.Name: Joe Foss Field
Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain adequate airspeed after shutting down one engine, which resulted in an inadvertent aerodynamic stall and impact with terrain. Contributing to the accident was the pilots failure to follow the guidance contained in the pilots operating handbook, which advised feathering the propeller of the secured engine and retracting the flaps and landing gear.

Airport.Name: Watertown Regional Airport
Report.Status: A total loss of engine power during initial climb for undetermined reasons.

Airport.Name: Hartsfield - Jackson Atlanta I
Report.Status: the failure of the captain of N303DQ to maintain a safe clearance from N583NW that was stopped on the taxiway.

A total loss of engine power during initial climb for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examination of the airframe and engine did not reveal any anomalies that would have precluded normal operation.

Airport.Name: Scottsdale
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain adequate separation behind a corporate jet, which resulted in an encounter with wake turbulence and a subsequent loss of control.

Airport.Name: Nanwalek
Report.Status: The pilots decision to takeoff from a contaminated runway with unfavorable wind conditions, and his failure to maintain airspeed during the initial climb, which resulted in an aerodynamic stall. Contributing to the accident was the operators inadequate procedures for operational control and dispatch.

Airport.Name: Hughes
Report.Status: The pilot did not clear the area surrounding the airplane prior to taxi, resulting in the airplane contacting a piece of baggage.

Airport.Name: Cheyenne Regional
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate compensation for the crosswind, which resulted in a loss of directional control.

Airport.Name: Mesquite Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's improper preflight planning, which resulted in a loss of engine power due to fuel exhaustion.

Airport.Name: Gwinnett County Airport
Report.Status: The mechanic's improper installation and lubrication of the bushing on the right main landing gear truss assembly, which resulted in the landing gear not locking in the down position.

Airport.Name: Pegasus McMurdo, Antarctica
Report.Status: an aerodynamic stall induced by an inadvertent autopilot Home command.  The Home command was entered following a loss of the direct radio link due to improperly set failsafe settings, and an unintentional latching of Home mode from an earlier functionality test.

Airport.Name: Kwigillingok
Report.Status: The pilots decision to continue visual flight into instrument meteorological conditions with moderate icing, which resulted in structural icing and an aerodynamic stall.

Airport.Name: Denver International Airport
Report.Status: The snowplow operators incapacitation due to fatigue, which resulted in the snowplow contacting a parked airplane. Contributing to the incident was the companys lack of a policy regarding employee fatigue.

Airport.Name: The Florida Keys Marathon Airp
Report.Status: The pilot did not ensure that there was sufficient fuel aboard the airplane before initiating the flight, which resulted in temporary fuel starvation and an interruption in engine power during maneuvering.  Contributing to the accident was the pilots decision to continue with the ditching after engine power was restored.

Airport.Name: Eldorado Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate in-flight planning and decision-making, which resulted in a loss of control during a crosswind landing.

Airport.Name: Craig Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's in-flight loss of control during climb after a banner pickup. Contributing to the accident was the pilot's impairment due to marijuana.

Airport.Name: Del Norte Kent Rominger Field
Report.Status: The pilot's loss of directional control during the landing roll, which resulted in a runway excursion. Contributing to the accident were the sensitivity of the brake system and the certified flight instructor pilot's delayed remedial action.

Airport.Name: San Angelo
Report.Status: A loss of engine power for undetermined reasons.
Failure of the rear crankshaft gear dowel pin due to improper installation, which resulted in a total loss of engine power.

Airport.Name: Phoenix Deer Valley
Report.Status: The pilots inability to maintain directional control during the landing roll for reasons that could not be determined because impact damage precluded determination of the preaccident functionality of the braking and steering systems.

Airport.Name: Fitchburg Municipal Airport
Report.Status: A partial loss of engine power due to the formation of carburetor ice and the flight instructor's improper application of carburetor heat.

Airport.Name: Willmar Municipal Airport-John
Report.Status: The pilot landed without lowering the landing gear.
The total loss of engine power due to fuel exhaustion and the pilots inadequate preflight inspection, which did not correctly identify the airplanes fuel quantity before departure.
The flight crews loss of airplane control.

Airport.Name: Tri-State Airport
Report.Status: The inadequate communication among ground crew personnel, which resulted in the airplanes collision with a deice truck.

Airport.Name: Roy E. Ray
Report.Status: The pilot's inability to maintain control of the airplane for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examination of the rudder control system did not reveal any anomalies that would have precluded control of the airplane.

Airport.Name: Richland Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper landing flare and inadequate directional control during landing.

Airport.Name: McGahan Industrial
Report.Status: The pilot's improper identification of the runway surface. Contributing to the accident was the snow covering the runway lights.

Airport.Name: Private
Report.Status: The pilots loss of directional control during the landing roll, which resulted in a runway excursion. Contributing to the accident was the sunglare.

Airport.Name: Camarillo Airport
Report.Status: A partial loss of engine power during cruise flight due to incorrectly installed airframe components, which came into contact with a high pressure fuel line and resulted in its failure. Contributing to the accident was an undetermined failure of the primary landing gear extension system that could not be identified due to extensive damage.

The flight's continued operation through an area containing substantial convective weather activity. Contributing to the accident was the air traffic control/traffic management unit's lack of awareness and recognition of the effect of weather movement on the departure route in use and the flight crew's acceptance of a route and limited weather deviation that was inadequate to maintain a safe distance from the thunderstorms in the area.

Airport.Name: Honolulu International Airport
Report.Status: The student pilots improper landing flare and inadequate directional control while performing an aborted landing.
The pilot's decision to land on unsuitable terrain, which resulted in the airplane nosing over.

Airport.Name: Chehalis Airport
Report.Status: The pilot did not correctly manage his glide profile during a simulated engine-out forced landing. Contributing to the accident was the pilot's decision not to add additional engine power, which resulted in a runway undershoot.

Airport.Name: Jackson-Evers Int'l
Report.Status: The separation of the propeller blade tip due to fatigue cracking that initiated at the blades leading edge.

Airport.Name: Sarasota/Bradenton Intl
Report.Status: The student pilots loss of directional control during the landing roll.

Airport.Name: Baltimore/Washington Internati
Report.Status: The pilot-in-command's failure to obtain the proper touchdown point or landing reference speed and failure to initiate a go-around when it became evident that the airplane was landing long and fast. Contributing to the incident was a lack of effective flight crew coordination and communication.

Airport.Name: Merrill Field
Report.Status: The pilot's premature power reduction, which resulted in a runway undershoot.

Airport.Name: Dillingham Airfield
Report.Status: The pilot's improper landing flare and inadequate recovery from a bounced landing.

Airport.Name: Charles B. Wheeler Downtown
Report.Status: The failure of the nosewheel steering pushrod, which resulted in a loss of airplane directional control and runway excursion.
an inadvertent encounter with Clear Air Turbulence that resulted in serious injuries to two crewmembers.

Airport.Name: Dinsmore
Report.Status: The flight instructor's delayed remedial action, inadequate recovery from a bounced landing, and failure to attain/maintain adequate airspeed during an attempted go-around.

Airport.Name: San Francisco International
Report.Status: the driver's failure to ensure that the belt loader was clear of the airplane before turning.

Airport.Name: Stibnite Mine
Report.Status: The pilot did not reduce the airplanes descent rate prior to the landing flare/touchdown, which resulted in a hard landing.

Airport.Name: Gilbert Airport
Report.Status: The flight instructors delayed remedial action to prevent the airplane from hitting the hangar door. Contributing to the accident was the student pilot's misuse of the airplane's throttle, and his incorrect use of the wheel brakes.

Airport.Name: John F. Kennedy International
Report.Status: The failure of the American Airlines aviation maintenance technicians to properly reassemble the two-piece bracket and spray shield on the integrated drive generator fuel-oil heat exchanger that caused a fuel leak that sprayed out and ignited on hot engine cases. Contributing to the cause of the fire was the 767 Aircraft Maintenance Manuals lack of any graphical or pictorial displays of the correct assembly of the two-piece bracket and spray shield.
The non-instrument-rated pilots poor planning and continued visual flight rules flight into instrument meteorological conditions and failure to maintain clearance from mountainous terrain.

Airport.Name: Kendall-Tamiami
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper flare and recovery from a bounced landing.

Airport.Name: Phifer Airfield
Report.Status: The flight crews loss of directional control during landing on an ice- and water-contaminated runway, which resulted in a runway excursion.

Airport.Name: PORTLAND INTL JETPORT
Report.Status: The fracture of the fan mid shaft due to a stress corrosion cracking initiated by local regions of corrosion pitting, which resulted from oil migration within the shaft and its subsequent degradation.

Airport.Name: Warrenton-Fauquier
Report.Status: The student pilot's failure to follow instruction and to relinquish control of the airplane to the flight instructor in a timely manner, which resulted in a runway excursion.

Airport.Name: Hollister Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain adequate airspeed during the initial climb, which resulted in an aerodynamic stall and a subsequent hard landing, loss of directional control, and ground loop.

Airport.Name: Weedon Field Airport
Report.Status: An inadvertent collision with a deer during a night landing.

Airport.Name: Stibnite Airport
Report.Status: The pilot did not maintain directional control while landing on a snow-contaminated runway.

Airport.Name: Iliamna
Report.Status: the maintenance personnel's failure to install the cotter pins that secured castellated nuts on the left elevator vertical hinge bolts, which resulted in the left elevator partially detaching in flight. Contributing to the accident was the failure of maintenance personnel to document the non-routine maintenance procedure that was used to remove and reinstall the elevator during maintenance.

Airport.Name: Pickens County Airport
Report.Status: The pilots' inadequate preflight inspection that failed to detect water-contaminated fuel, which resulted in a total loss of engine power.

Airport.Name: Denver International Airport
Report.Status: A failure of the nose landing gear end cap due to fatigue. Contributing to the failure were the ineffective inspection and the unknown effect of grain direction on fatigue life.

Airport.Name: Essex County Airport
Report.Status: The student pilots loss of directional control during a crosswind landing.

An in-flight encounter with forecasted turbulence, which resulted in a serious injury to a flight attendant. Contributing to the accident was the flight attendant not being seated with her seatbelt fastened when the encounter occurred.

Airport.Name: Reykjavik

Report.Status: The airplane's encounter with moderate turbulence during cruise flight, which resulted in a serious injury to a flight attendant.
The loss of engine power during climb due to carburetor icing. Contributing to the accident was the limited travel of the carburetor heat valve which prevented application of maximum carburetor heat.
an encounter with convective turbulence that resulted in injury to a passenger who was not seated when the seatbelt sign was illuminated.

Airport.Name: Dixie Valley
Report.Status: The airplanes encounter with forecast low-level windshear conditions during takeoff, which resulted in a loss of lift.

Airport.Name: Jimmy Carter Regional Airport
Report.Status: The failure of maintenance personnel to properly secure a portion of the right wing leading edge, which resulted in the separation of the associated section of the leading edge during takeoff and the loss of directional control during the subsequent landing.

Airport.Name: Stinson Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's inadvertent overboost of the turbocharged engine during initial climb, which resulted in detonation and a partial loss of engine power followed by the pilot's failure to maintain airspeed and the instructor's delayed remedial action, which resulted in an aerodynamic stall. Contributing to the accident was the instructor's improper judgment in acting as a pilot with disqualifying medical conditions and while taking impairing medications.
the flight attendant inadvertently tripping over a passenger's luggage strap that was protruding into the isle.

Airport.Name: Front Range Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's improper decision to taxi in wind conditions that exceeded the airplanes capability.

Airport.Name: Somerset Airport
Report.Status: The pilot receiving instructions inadvertent movement of the pitch trim control to the nose-down position while attempting a go-around.

Airport.Name: PHILADELPHIA INTL
Report.Status: an inadvertent encounter with clear air turbulence during descent.

Airport.Name: Ted Stevens Anchorage Int'l
Report.Status: The flightcrew's loss of visual reference to the runway after encountering severe in-flight icing conditions, which resulted in a loss of control while landing and exceedence of the capabilities of the airplane's windscreen anti-ice systems. Contributing to this incident was the failure of the approach controller to relay a pilot report of severe icing conditions near the route of flight to the incident flight crew.

Airport.Name: Van Voorhees Field NAS Fallon
Report.Status:
fuel exhaustion following missed approaches due to deficient ATC handling under weather conditions which were significantly lower than forecast.  The second missed approach may have been initiated due to limited pilot instrument proficiency.

Contributing to the severity of the accident was the pilot's decision to attempt an emergency landing in low visibility instead of ejecting when fuel exhaustion was imminent.  

Also contributing to the accident was an organizational and oversight environment which did not require airman, aircraft, or risk management controls or standards expected of a commercial civil aviation operation.

Airport.Name: Dekalb Peachtree Airport
Report.Status: An in-flight collision with birds during cruise flight.

Airport.Name: Hollandale Municipal
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control while taxiing in gusty wind conditions.

The inadequate servicing and maintenance of the engine and the airplane owner and maintenance personnel's disregard of the manufacturer's recommended engine overhaul schedule and service bulletins, which resulted in an in-flight internal failure and seizure of the engine.
The pilot's decision to take off from an unsuitable off-airport site.
An inadvertent encounter with a bird during cruise flight.
The pilot's decision to depart in marginal visual meteorological conditions, and his continued visual flight into instrument meteorological conditions.

Airport.Name: St. Johns Industrial Air Park
Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain directional control when the right brake locked up during the landing roll for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examination did not reveal any anomalies that would have precluded normal operation.

Airport.Name: Hays Regional Airport
Report.Status: A failure of the nose landing gear end cap due to fatigue. Contributing to the failure were the ineffective inspection and the unknown effect of grain direction on fatigue life.

Airport.Name: Caldwell Industrial Airport
Report.Status: The pilot did not properly secure the airplane before starting the engine by manually rotating the propeller, which resulted in the inadvertent movement of the airplane.

Airport.Name: Warrenton-Fauquier Airport
Report.Status: Maintenance personnel's failure to identify stress corrosion cracking in the stabilator control cable during the most recent inspection, and the subsequent failure of the cable on the flight after the inspection.

The flight instructor's decision to continue flight into the area of reduced visibility and the pilots subsequent failure to maintain clearance from the hilly terrain while operating in an area of low ceilings, rain, and fog.

Airport.Name: LUIS MUNOZ MARIN INTL
Report.Status: the flight crew's failure to maintain adequate airspeed after shutting down the right engine due to an in-flight fire in one of the right augmentors. The failure to maintain airspeed resulted in either an aerodynamic stall or a loss of directional control.

Airport.Name: Charleston Executive
Report.Status: The pilot's improper landing flare, which resulted in a hard landing.

Airport.Name: Hollister Municipal
Report.Status: The pilots lack of situational awareness regarding the surrounding terrain while descending during dark night conditions, which resulted in controlled flight into terrain.

Airport.Name: Private
Report.Status: The pilots inadequate compensation for the wind conditions during takeoff.

A total loss of engine power due to the improper installation of the crankshaft gear bolt or lockplate by maintenance personnel. Contributing to the accident was the lack of suitable terrain for a forced landing.

Airport.Name: Houston Southwest Airport
Report.Status: The pilot did not maintain adequate crosswind correction during the landing flare and the flight instructor's delayed remedial action.

Airport.Name: Massey Ranch Airpark
Report.Status: The pilot's improper flare, which resulted in a hard landing. Contributing to the accident was the flight instructor's inadequate remedial action.

Airport.Name: Belfast Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The flight instructors failure to ensure the radio was set correctly to activate the pilot-controlled lighting, which resulted in poor positioning for a proper landing and a subsequent off-runway forced landing during an attempted go-around. Airport.Name: Eagle Creek Airpark
Report.Status: The student pilot did not maintain directional control while practicing a soft-field takeoff.

Airport.Name: West Woodward Airport
Report.Status: The airplanes encounter with severe turbulence during cruise flight, which resulted in a serious injury to a flight attendant.

Airport.Name: Clearwater Air Park
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain airplane control during takeoff and the flight instructor's inadequate supervision, which resulted in a runway excursion.

Airport.Name: Jean Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot did not maintain directional control during the landing roll.

Airport.Name: Beaver County Airport
Report.Status: The operators maintenance personnels improper adjustment of the engine's fuel system, which resulted in a total loss of engine power.

Airport.Name: Conrad Airport
Report.Status: The pilot did not maintain directional control of the airplane due to ice and slushy snow on the runway during the landing roll.

Airport.Name: Vance Brand
Report.Status: The inadequate visual lookout by the pilots of both airplanes, which resulted in a mid-air collision.

Airport.Name: Shawnee Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to land with sufficient runway remaining to stop, which resulted in an unsuccessful aborted landing, inadvertent stall, and collision with terrain.

Airport.Name: Hernando County Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's improper landing flare, which resulted in a hard landing.

Airport.Name: Sheets Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during a go-around maneuver in gusty crosswind conditions.

Airport.Name: W K Kellogg Airport
Report.Status: The maintenance technician did not remove the tow bar prior to the flight.

Airport.Name: Houston Southwest Airport
Report.Status: A total loss of engine power during landing approach for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examination of the airframe and engine did not reveal any anomalies that would have precluded normal operation.

Airport.Name: Chalet Suzanne Air Strip
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate preflight preparation and fuel management, which resulted in a total loss of engine power due to fuel starvation.

Airport.Name: Winterset Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The loss of oil pressure to the No. 4 connecting rod journal and the subsequent loss of engine power.

Airport.Name: Coastal Flying Service
Report.Status: The improper positioning of the hopper vent, which allowed chemicals to escape and cover the airplane's windshield.

A complete loss of engine power due to fuel exhaustion as a result of the pilot's failure to verify that sufficient fuel was onboard prior to flight. Airport.Name: San Marcos Municipal Airport

Airport.Name: Ann Arbor Municipal
Report.Status: The student pilot's failure to maintain airplane control on takeoff, which resulted in an aerodynamic stall and collision with terrain.

Airport.Name: Geoarge Bush Intercontinental
Report.Status:
the nose landing gear alternate release handle was not pulled with sufficient enough force or distance to release the uplocks and allow extension of the nose landing gear.

Contributing to the accident was the dissimilar pull force and pull length set on the flight simulator that was used for flight crew training of alternate landing gear extension procedures and the lack of information available to crew members advising of the dissimilar pull force.
The pilot did not maintain sufficient airspeed while maneuvering, which resulted in an aerodynamic stall at a low altitude.
A total loss of engine power due to a catastrophic engine failure, the origin of which could not be determined during postaccident examination.
The pilot's inadequate preflight planning and in-flight fuel management, which resulted in a total loss of engine power due to fuel exhaustion.

Airport.Name: Lee's Summit Muni Airport
Report.Status: The student pilots loss of directional control while landing.

Report.Status: The student pilot's improper landing flare, which resulted in a bounced landing and loss of directional control.

Airport.Name: Blue Ribbon Airport

Airport.Name: Prescott
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate compensation for a crosswind during takeoff, which resulted in a loss of directional control.
an inadvertent encounter with mountain wave turbulence.

Airport.Name: Madison Airport
Report.Status: A total loss of engine power due to fuel exhaustion. The pilots inability to maintain control of the airplane and arrest a steep spiral dive while maneuvering for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examination could not identify any anomalies that would have precluded normal operation prior to the inflight breakup.

Airport.Name: Joe Foss Field Airport
Report.Status: The failure of the normal and emergency landing gear system to fully retract or extend the landing gear for reasons that could not be determined during postaccident examinations, which resulted in a partial gear-up landing.
The pilot's diverted attention, which resulted in a loss of control while maneuvering the airplane at a low altitude.

Airport.Name: Mahlon Sweet Field Airport

The pilot's attempt to take off with the carburetor heat in the hot position, which limited the airplanes performance, and the pilot's subsequent failure to maintain adequate airspeed, which resulted in an aerodynamic stall.
Impingement of the elevator control by foreign objects (clamp, glove) left in the flight control path by the pilot/owner or maintenance personnel.
A separation of the right main landing gear suspension strut assembly due to overstress, which resulted in the collapse of the main landing gear while landing.

Airport.Name: Lake Wales Municipal Airport

Report.Status: Collision with a deer during the takeoff roll.

Airport.Name: Naval Air Station Point Mugu
Report.Status:
the pilot's decision to continue the flight with a known fuel imbalance condition that resulted in a loss of lateral control when the imbalance exceeded the known capabilities of the airplane.  The fuel imbalance was due to incomplete refueling and an ineffective preflight inspection by the pilot.  The imbalance was further complicated by an incorrectly assembled fuel transfer valve and motor combination.  

Contributing to the severity of the accident was the pilot's delayed decision to eject prior to exceeding the ejection seat envelope.  Also contributing to the accident was (1) the Navy's oversight environment, which did not require airman, aircraft, and risk management controls or standards expected of a commercial civil aviation operation, and (2) ATAC's organizational environment, which did not include CRM training to promote good aeronautical decision-making and ORM guidance to mitigate hazards.  Also contributing to the accident were the design features of the airplane, which were typical of its generation, including the lack of accurate fuel quantity indications, the design of the fuel transfer valve; and the maintenance program's lack of clearly documented procedures and type-specific training for the Hunter.

Airport.Name: Private
Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain clearance from a guy wire during an agricultural application pass.

Airport.Name: Des Moines International
Report.Status: A temporary loss of control during cruise flight for reasons that could not be determined because postincident examination of the autopilot, pitch trim systems, and horizontal stabilizer revealed no anomalies consistent with a loss of control.

Airport.Name: Albany International
Report.Status: A total loss of engine power for reasons that could not be determined during the postaccident investigation and testing.
The pilot's failure to maintain clearance from power lines during the aerial application flight.

Airport.Name: Private
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper landing flare and the flight instructor's inadequate remedial action, which resulted in a hard landing.

A failure of an engine cylinder exhaust valve due to the buildup of lead deposits on the valve stem and fatigue cracking of the valve stem, resulting in a total loss of engine power, and the loss of the propeller. Contributing to the accident was the lack of design standards or guidance for assembly and maintenance of light sport aircraft.
The improper installation of the wastegate controller O-ring, which resulted in a partial loss of engine power.
The mechanic's failure to adequately torque the right magneto attachment nuts, allowing the right magneto to come loose, which allowed engine oil to escape, causing the engine to seize.

Airport.Name: Private
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain airplane control during the takeoff roll. Contributing to the accident was the rough condition of the runway.

Airport.Name: Private
Report.Status: The pilots inadequate preflight planning, which resulted in the airplanes loading beyond its maximum gross weight.
A partial loss of engine power for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examination of the engine revealed no anomalies.

Airport.Name: P K Airpark
Report.Status: The pilot's decision to land in a grassy area next to a paved runway, which resulted in impact with a ditch and subsequent nose landing gear collapse.

Airport.Name: Braga - Ponte de Lima
Report.Status: This report is under the jurisdiction and control of the Portuguese Government.

Airport.Name: King Abdulaziz International

Report.Status: The flight instructors selection of the wrong route while flying in mountainous terrain at a high-density altitude, which resulted in the airplane impacting terrain when the increase in elevation exceeded the airplanes climb performance.

Airport.Name: Deland Municipal
Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain airplane control on final approach in gusting wind conditions. Contributing to the accident was the pilots decision to operate in an environment of thunderstorms and rapidly deteriorating weather.

Airport.Name: Llano Municipal
Report.Status: The flight instructors delayed remedial action and inadequate supervision during practice traffic pattern work.  Contributing to the accident was the flight instructors use of sedating medication on the day of the accident and airplanes high angle of attack at a low altitude during the traffic pattern turn, which prevented recovery during an aerodynamic stall.

Airport.Name: Big River Lakes
Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain adequate ground clearance during his landing approach, which resulted in a collision with terrain.

Airport.Name: Sandpoint
Report.Status: A deer strike during the landing flare. Contributing to the accident was the airports lack of any deer incursion prevention measures, such as an airport perimeter fence.

Airport.Name: Snohomish County Airport
Report.Status: A hard landing likely made by the private pilot on a solo flight that preceded the dual instructional flight during which the wing damage became obvious.

Airport.Name: Millville Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilot receiving instruction failed to maintain airplane control during the simulated engine-out landing. Contributing to the accident was the flight instructor's failure to take timely remedial action.
The total loss of engine power due to a fatigue failure of the rocker arm journal casting of the rocker arm cap.

Airport.Name: Charles B. Wheeler Downtown Ai
Report.Status: The flight crews failure to ensure that the cargo door was properly fastened before departure.

Airport.Name: David Jay Perry Airport
Report.Status: The commercial pilot did not attain the proper touchdown point during the landing, which resulted in a premature touchdown and an impact with the edge of the runway surface.

Airport.Name: Nephi Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's inability to maintain airplane control due to an encounter with a microburst/downdraft that exceeded the climb performance capabilities of the airplane.

Airport.Name: Wood County
Report.Status: The pilot receiving instruction's excessive braking during the landing roll, which resulted in a loss of control.
The flight instructors delayed response in correcting the student pilots improper landing flare, which resulted in a hard landing.

Airport.Name: Samuels Field Airport
Report.Status: The flight instructor's decision to turn the fuel selector to the off position and his delayed remedial actions to restart the engine, which resulted in fuel starvation and a subsequent forced landing.
The pilots selection of a flightpath toward rising terrain that exceeded the climb capability of the airplane.

Airport.Name: Juneau International
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control of the tailwheel-equipped airplane during landing, resulting in a ground loop. Contributing to the accident was the flight instructor's failure to adequately monitor the landing.
The student pilots failure to maintain directional control of the airplane while maneuvering at a low altitude.

Airport.Name: Council Bluffs Municipal
Report.Status: An unlocking of the excessively worn tailwheel lock mechanism, which resulted in a loss of directional control during landing.

Airport.Name: Nantucket Memorial Airport
